        "subtype": "bot_message",
        "text": "*[Bug 19005] New: as.POSIXlt may produce different attr(,\"tzone\")[2:3] depending on the order of the calls and values*\n<https:\/\/bugs.r-project.org\/show_bug.cgi?id=19005>\n\n            Bug ID: 19005\n           Summary: as.POSIXlt may produce different attr(,\"tzone\")[2:3]\n                    depending on the order of the calls and values\n           Product: R\n           Version: R 4.5.x\n          Hardware: All\n                OS: All\n            Status: UNCONFIRMED\n          Severity: trivial\n          Priority: P5\n         Component: Low-level\n          Assignee: <mailto:R-core@R-project.org|R-core@R-project.org>\n          Reporter: <mailto:ikrylov@disroot.org|ikrylov@disroot.org>\n\nOriginally [reported on\nR-devel](<https:\/\/stat.ethz.ch\/pipermail\/r-devel\/2026-January\/084326.html>) by\nMichael Chirico: in some cases `attr(as.POSIXlt(...), 'tzone')` will differ\nbetween the first and subsequent calls to `as.POSIXlt`.\n\nWith or without system tzcode:\n\n```\nTZ=Europe\/London R -q -s -e '\n .Internal(as.POSIXlt(1, \"\")) |&gt;\n attr(\"tzone\") |&gt;\n _[2] |&gt;\n replicate(n=3)\n'\n# [1] \"GMT\" \"BST\" \"BST\"\n```\n\nBut:\n\n```\nTZ=Europe\/London R -q -s -e '\n .Internal(as.POSIXlt(c(1, 1771084813), \"\")) |&gt; attr(\"tzone\")\n .Internal(as.POSIXlt(c(1), \"\")) |&gt; attr(\"tzone\")\n'\n# [1] \"Europe\/London\" \"GMT\"           \"BST\"          \n# [1] \"Europe\/London\" \"GMT\"           \"BST\"          \n```\n\nAs [explained](<https:\/\/stat.ethz.ch\/pipermail\/r-devel\/2026-January\/084341.html>)\nby Georgi Boshnakov, `attr(., 'tzone')[2] == \"BST\"` would be correct for UK in\nJanuary 1970.\n\nIn `do_asPOSIXlt`, R first calls `tzset()` and then reads the timezone names\nfrom `tzname`. As the comment says (\"Do now as localtime may change tzname\"),\nthis is deliberate. The problem is that during a later call to `as.POSIXlt`,\n`tzset` [does not\noverwrite](<https:\/\/sourceware.org\/git\/?p=glibc.git;a=blob;f=time\/tzset.c;h=df1c9fdd6edd666163e933470650645f72f864d6;hb=HEAD#l388>)\n`tzname` because there was no change in `$TZ`, so when R re-reads `tzname` it\nsees `{ \"BST\", \"BST\" }` instead of the `{ \"GMT\", \"BST\" }` that was there the\nfirst time. As a result, `attr(., 'tzone')[2:3]` depends on the last element of\nthe previously converted vector.\n\nShould R somehow try harder to cause the tzcode to reset `tzname` before\nreading it in subsequent calls to `as.POSIXlt`? Unlike the first element of the\nvector, `attr(., 'tzone')[2:3]` should be mostly inconsequential as different\nDST rules apply at different points in time, so there may be no valid set of\nvalues applicable to the whole `POSIXlt` vector. Some conversions already\nproduce a 1-element `tzone` attribute instead of the documented 3-element\nvector:\n\n```\nas.POSIXlt('1970-01-01 01:00:01', tz = 'Europe\/London') |&gt; attr('tzone')\n# [1] \"Europe\/London\"\n```",
